"use strict";(self.webpackChunkLuminescentBlade=self.webpackChunkLuminescentBlade||[]).push([[411],{6411:(f,s,o)=>{o.r(s),o.d(s,{MainComponent:()=>h,MiscModule:()=>p,StrategiesComponent:()=>u,miscRoutes:()=>c});var d=o(6814),r=o(9945),e=o(5879);const m=function(){return["strategies"]},y=function(){return["musings"]};let h=(()=>{class t{}return t.\u0275fac=function(a){return new(a||t)},t.\u0275cmp=e.Xpm({type:t,selectors:[["lbmisc-main"]],decls:11,vars:4,consts:[[1,"dame-da-ne"],[3,"routerLink"]],template:function(a,n){1&a&&(e.TgZ(0,"h2",0),e._uU(1,"Miscellaneous"),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(2,"ul")(3,"li")(4,"a",1)(5,"h3"),e._uU(6,"Fire Emblem Strategies"),e.qZA()()(),e.TgZ(7,"li")(8,"a",1)(9,"h3"),e._uU(10,"Musings"),e.qZA()()()()),2&a&&(e.xp6(4),e.Q6J("routerLink",e.DdM(2,m)),e.xp6(4),e.Q6J("routerLink",e.DdM(3,y)))},dependencies:[r.rH],styles:["ul[_ngcontent-%COMP%]{list-style:none;text-align:center;padding:0}"]}),t})();var l=o(5131);let u=(()=>{class t{}return t.\u0275fac=function(a){return new(a||t)},t.\u0275cmp=e.Xpm({type:t,selectors:[["lbmisc-strategies"]],decls:10,vars:1,consts:[[1,"dame-da-ne"],[3,"url"],["slot","title"],["slot","image"],["src","/assets/misc/strategy/ayra/talk2.png",1,"lb-misc__strategy-ayra"],["slot","description"]],template:function(a,n){1&a&&(e.TgZ(0,"h2",0),e._uU(1,"Fire Emblem Strategies"),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(2,"lib-description-link",1),e.ynx(3,2),e._uU(4,"Ayra's Recruitment: Contactless Edition"),e.BQk(),e.ynx(5,3),e._UZ(6,"img",4),e.BQk(),e.ynx(7,5),e.TgZ(8,"p"),e._uU(9,"Have you ever played Fire Emblem: Geneology of the Holy War and struggled with Ayra's recruitment? If so, this guide is for you. This is a safe, reliable, risk-free way to recruit Ayra in FE4. You won't need to fight her, not even once!"),e.qZA(),e.BQk(),e.qZA()),2&a&&(e.xp6(2),e.Q6J("url","ayra-recruitment"))},dependencies:[l.Q],styles:["img.lb-misc__strategy-ayra[_ngcontent-%COMP%]{position:absolute;width:480px;top:-50px;left:-225px}"]}),t})();const c=[{path:"",pathMatch:"full",component:h},{path:"strategies",pathMatch:"full",component:u},{path:"strategies/ayra-recruitment",pathMatch:"full",component:(()=>{class t{}return t.\u0275fac=function(a){return new(a||t)},t.\u0275cmp=e.Xpm({type:t,selectors:[["lbmisc-ayra-recruitment"]],decls:28,vars:0,consts:[["datetime","2023-07-27",1,"article-date"],["src","/assets/misc/strategy/ayra/overview.png",1,"strategy-ayra__overview"],[1,"strategy-ayra__image-set"],["src","/assets/misc/strategy/ayra/1.png"],["src","/assets/misc/strategy/ayra/2.png"],["src","/assets/misc/strategy/ayra/3.png"],["src","/assets/misc/strategy/ayra/4.png"],["src","/assets/misc/strategy/ayra/5.png"],["src","/assets/misc/strategy/ayra/talk1.png"],["src","/assets/misc/strategy/ayra/talk2.png"]],template:function(a,n){1&a&&(e.TgZ(0,"article")(1,"h2"),e._uU(2," Ayra's Recruitment: Contactless Edition "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(3,"time",0),e._uU(4,"July 27, 2023"),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(5,"p"),e._uU(6," From all my years of playing Fire Emblem 4 and talking to people who's also played Fire Emblem 4, recruiting Ayra seems to be a pretty common pain point. Ayra's got massive base stats and Astra, and is likely to kill most of your units on contact--or it's kind of a tossup who dies if you do it with Sigurd. A common approach is baiting her with Alec since he has Nihil to negate Astra, but he does have to also meet an 11 attack speed threshold unarmed otherwise Ayra doubles him. This can be secured with speed ring, but then you'd have to let him take the speed ring village instead of more optimal candidates. However, you don't really need to actually bait Ayra directly. "),e.qZA(),e._UZ(7,"img",1),e.TgZ(8,"p"),e._uU(9," Above is a diagram I made from playing through chapter 1. I've highlighted the range of the left side fighter, but also Ayra's range. The gameplan, is to get Sigurd to go toward the right and trigger the movement of the fighters without being directly in range of Ayra, while someone else will move to the X marked toward the north of the forest to pull her AI. They will not directly engage in combat with Ayra. The entirety of Sigurd's army should follow the green marked path that goes around north then down west of the forest north of Genoa, since that both kites Ayra and moves them closer to Marpha, which is where they need to be. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(10,"p"),e._uU(11,"Below is a step by step of how I played it out:"),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(12,"div",2),e._UZ(13,"img",3)(14,"img",4),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(15,"p"),e._uU(16,"Here's a before and after of Sigurd in position to move in, and Sigurd + Quan's positions after I moved them into place for the initial movement trigger. I used Quan as my kiter here, but anyone weaker than Sigurd will work---which is to say anyone else will work. In the second image, I've highlighted Sigurd's next position--still out of Ayra's range, and he can even easily pick up a kill on one of the axe guys and canto into position after. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(17,"div",2),e._UZ(18,"img",5)(19,"img",6)(20,"img",7),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(21,"p"),e._uU(22,"Keep moving the Kiter just outside of her range. This will cause Ayra's AI to chase the kiter and after the second turn of her movement she should be far from Sigurd, so he can start his assault on Genoa."),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(23,"div",2),e._UZ(24,"img",8)(25,"img",9),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(26,"p"),e._uU(27," Once Sigurd seizes, Ayra will double back to check on Shannan. Keep Sigurd out of her attack range and move in to talk as soon as you get a chance. This gets you Ayra without ever having to fight her at all. "),e.qZA()())},styles:[".strategy-ayra__overview[_ngcontent-%COMP%]{display:block;margin:0 auto;max-width:500px;width:100%}.strategy-ayra__image-set[_ngcontent-%COMP%]{display:flex;width:100%;max-width:100%;justify-content:space-evenly;flex-wrap:wrap}.strategy-ayra__image-set[_ngcontent-%COMP%]   img[_ngcontent-%COMP%]{display:block;width:300px;margin-bottom:24px}"]}),t})()},{path:"musings",pathMatch:"full",component:(()=>{class t{}return t.\u0275fac=function(a){return new(a||t)},t.\u0275cmp=e.Xpm({type:t,selectors:[["lbmisc-musings"]],decls:10,vars:1,consts:[[1,"dame-da-ne"],[3,"url"],["slot","title"],["slot","image"],["src","/assets/misc/musings/ayrakiryu.png",1,"lb-misc__musings-ayra-kiryu"],["slot","description"]],template:function(a,n){1&a&&(e.TgZ(0,"h2",0),e._uU(1,"Musings"),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(2,"lib-description-link",1),e.ynx(3,2),e._uU(4,"On Kiryu Kazuma and Ayra of Isaach"),e.BQk(),e.ynx(5,3),e._UZ(6,"img",4),e.BQk(),e.ynx(7,5),e.TgZ(8,"p"),e._uU(9," Ayra has been my favorite character in Fire Emblem since I played FE4 back in 2010, and despite playing through the entire series, and all the new releases that came out after, none has surpassed my favor for her. I didn't fully understand why, until in 2022, where I played the Yakuza series and met Kiryu Kazuma... "),e.qZA(),e.BQk(),e.qZA()),2&a&&(e.xp6(2),e.Q6J("url","ayra-kiryu"))},dependencies:[l.Q],styles:[".lb-misc__musings-ayra-kiryu[_ngcontent-%COMP%]{display:block;position:absolute;width:160px}"]}),t})()},{path:"musings/ayra-kiryu",pathMatch:"full",component:(()=>{class t{}return t.\u0275fac=function(a){return new(a||t)},t.\u0275cmp=e.Xpm({type:t,selectors:[["lbmisc-ayra-kiryu-essay"]],decls:45,vars:0,consts:[["role","doc-subtitle"],["datetime","2023-07-27",1,"article-date"]],template:function(a,n){1&a&&(e.TgZ(0,"article")(1,"h2"),e._uU(2," On Kiryu Kazuma and Ayra of Isaach "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(3,"div",0),e._uU(4," Or, How Kiryu Kazuma Made Me Realize Why Ayra Is My Favorite Fire Emblem Character And It's Not Even Close "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(5,"time",1),e._uU(6,"July 27, 2023"),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(7,"p"),e._uU(8," So I've been a Fire Emblem fan for a long-ass time\u2014since \u201809 or \u201810, I forget exactly when\u2014and by the end of \u201810 I\u2019ve played most of the Fire Emblems that are available one way or another, including the Japan-exclusive Genealogy of the Holy War. I met Ayra and immediately I was drawn to her. While gen 2 characters are in a vacuum more powerful and I had a great time making Larcei, her daughter, into the strongest killing machine in the game\u2013and I love Larcei by the way she\u2019s also one of my favorite characters, in terms of characterization there was nobody that I vibed harder with than with Ayra. Her incredible introduction stuck with me and I think she\u2019s one of the coolest characters you can make with about 10-15 lines of dialogue. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(9,"p"),e._uU(10," Fast forward 13 years and I\u2019m still into Fire Emblem. I've played every mainline game that has been released\u2013and a couple of spinoffs\u2013and yet there still isn\u2019t a character I like more than Ayra. Those of you who knew me around \u201816 probably associate me with Ryoma. He\u2019s actually my #2. I have high praise for 3 Houses characterization as a whole and probably more Edelgard merch than a person really should\u2013she\u2019s actually #3, but given 3 Houses is new it just gets the merch when I actually have money to spare, so\u2014but the point stands. Despite characters getting more dialogue\u2013despite some of them getting really good dialogue, even, given my aforementioned fondness of the 3H cast as a whole\u2014Ayra remains at the top, the queen unchallenged in her throne. At this point I don\u2019t think it\u2019s possible for a Fire Emblem character to come close to her and only a 4 remake could create a character I like more by, well, just fleshing her out even more. It is not, however, until I played the Yakuza series until I realized just how true that really is. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(11,"p"),e._uU(12," So in 2022 I got into the Yakuza series, I started with 0, like many do, and already hit it off well with the younger, brasher, version of Kiryu (really\u2013both Kiryu and Majima, who both shot up to my number 1 and 2 vg protagonists, but only really Kiryu\u2019s relevant here). I had such a good time with 0 that it became my new favorite game of all time\u2014finishing the game for the first time was honestly an experience that I would love to experience all over again\u2013and so I jumped right into a months-long marathon of the Kiryu saga. My love for Kiryu grew further as I experienced his story as an older wiser father, and he\u2019s easily sitting at the absolute peak of fictional characters as far as my taste goes. Kiryu\u2019s a great protagonist even in a vacuum, but he also just hits everything I like in a character Just Right and that caused him to shoot up to #1 over pretty much everyone that came before. Kiryu is basically My Type personified. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(13,"p"),e._uU(14," And then it struck me that Ayra is an awful lot like him in some ways. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(15,"p"),e._uU(16," Now Ayra is written in 1996, and Kiryu in 2005, so really Ayra came first. Kiryu does have the benefit of having 7 games where he\u2019s the protagonist and substories to really flesh out his character compared to Ayra having about 15 lines, so he does have a really strong advantage in that department. And obviously, they are their own people and won\u2019t match one-to-one, but there are some major points of similarity I\u2019ve noticed and given how much I\u2019ve connected with Kiryu, the immovability of Ayra's throne, despite the cast of 700+ in all the Fire Emblems, becomes so much more clear. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(17,"p"),e._uU(18," Before I make the comparisons, I need to talk a bit about myself first for some context. While female I never particularly vibed with concepts like femininity and hate being placed in a box for it. Now I don\u2019t particularly have issues being perceived as female and I\u2019m not gonna actively make my life harder over something I don\u2019t feel all that strongly about, but what I do feel strongly about is people telling me I can\u2019t behave in a certain way because of those perceptions. I naturally behave in ways that people generally perceive to be more masculine (very often commented on by people in my parents generation) and while as a small child I\u2019ve tried to correct the myriad of my \u201cunfeminine\u201d behavior due to, well, children being impressionable and all, I\u2019ve since embraced that just ain\u2019t me, and I will not be constrained by it. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(19,"p"),e._uU(20," So there\u2019s that whole debate between Strong Female Characters vs stop writing women like men or whatever, this is a very simplified summary of that business and, while I\u2019m firmly in the \u201clet\u2019s write women like people and their femaleness is part of their experiences but it shouldn\u2019t be the core of their character before just being a person\u201d kinda deal, as a masc gal there\u2019s honestly very little female characters that are actually written \u201clike men\u201d both in the sense where male characters often don\u2019t have their maleness drive their characters and a lot of mainstream media \u201cStrong Female Characters\u201d really aren\u2019t and it\u2019s just people conflating strength and masculinity. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(21,"p"),e._uU(22," But Ayra\u2019s characterization hits the vibes I want right. She\u2019s straightforward, brutal, absolutely does not give a shit. She\u2019s self-described as not very feminine but doesn\u2019t particularly have a complex about it and I vibe with that\u2014I feel like in a lot of asian media, which I consume a lot of as a chinese person, when female characters are not traditionally feminine they get written with insecurities about their lack of perceived femininity and I do get that\u2019s a thing\u2013hell I\u2019ve had that thing when I was like, 10\u2013 so I\u2019m not gonna write it all off as bad writing, but I loved how unapologetic Ayra is about it. She just doesn\u2019t give a shit. She knows her worth and has strong boundaries.She\u2019s presented as a real threat. Her original design feels fairly neutral as far as the outfit choices go. Only after she\u2019s established as a popular character do IS start really heavily feminizing her outfit, which I\u2019m pretty annoyed about but that\u2019s for a different discussion. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(23,"p"),e._uU(24," Being tough isn\u2019t the only part of her personality, however\u2013she\u2019s immensely loyal, ride or die, even\u2014which is a trait I also find common in a lot of characters I like, and the friendship she develops with Sigurd is one of my favorite friendships in the series. Her core character motivation is protecting Shannan, both as family and as the last hope for her country, and I personally find motivations that do something that isn\u2019t just about one\u2019s self generally more compelling. She establishes all that and some international relations lore outside of the Granvale-Isaach conflict in the amount of lines given to a supporting cast member in a SNES game. She knows how to make it count. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(25,"p"),e._uU(26," In 2022, Ascended Mareeta gets into Fire Emblem Heroes and Ayra gets her first major piece of character interaction since FE4 itself. The next New Heroes banner after that, her son, Scathach is introduced, and she gets to interact with both him and his sister\u2013Ayra\u2019s daughter\u2013Larcei. I greatly enjoyed both\u2014FEH can be hit or miss when it comes to characterization but they\u2019ve written Ayra pretty well and both her Forging Bonds interaction sets were no exception, and even better when she finally gets to meet her kids as adults. Later that year I played Yakuza, and I decided to 100% Yakuza 6 because it\u2019s the easiest to do\u2013unfortunately in a lot of the others being good at the minigames kinda gate me\u2013otherwise I\u2019d absolutely 100% 0\u2013so on my legend replay for the 100%, out of curiosity, I decided to play the game with Chinese subtitles. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(27,"p"),e._uU(28," Now don\u2019t get me wrong, I think the English localization of Yakuza generally does a fantastic job especially with the difficulty of Yakuza being such a heavily steeped in Japanese culture game. But Chinese, given the whole kanji business, is just much closer to a language than Japanese, and as such generally tends to get across specific nuances in speech patterns a bit more easily. The way Kiryu talked in the Chinese localization really stuck with me. One day I decided to do the same for Ayra. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(29,"p"),e._uU(30," Despite my native language being Chinese I usually play FEH in English\u2013partially for the skill names and descriptions, and partially because sometimes the Chinese localization of FEH can be a little too literal and relying too much on shared kanji that may mean the same thing in a dictionary but don't\u2019 hold the same connotations. Despite that, the Chinese localization also did a pretty damn good job with Ayra\u2013but that\u2019s when I realized that she talks in a pretty similar way Kiryu does, at least based on vibes. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(31,"p"),e._uU(32," Now Kiryu doesn\u2019t particularly use much profanity in itself, but his words make him sound dangerous all the same. You can easily tell that he\u2019s a guy not to be messed with and there\u2019s even a couple of RGGO stories about how the way he talks created some misunderstandings because of what he considers normal speech sounds really violent to normal people. Ayra carries that same level of threatening in her way of talking\u2013not in the sense that she is literally threatening except in her intro which she absolutely is and does an absolutely bang up job of it, but it\u2019s a degree of brusque efficiency that not many fire emblem characters at all really achieve. As one of my good friends aptly puts it, Ayra talks like she\u2019s from the city while most of Fire Emblem talk like they\u2019re from the suburbs. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(33,"p"),e._uU(34," Given Kiryu is often touted as the image of positive masculinity on top of being my favorite fictional character and I\u2019ve always connected with Ayra on the level of relating with being masc-behaving women, having similar mannerisms in itself is quite enough to retroactively explain how Ayra held my top spot in Fire Emblem despite the myriads of tough gals (which as a whole I\u2019m very fond of and often do hold high places of favor as far as FE characters go) in the series because nobody else really acts the same way\u2013and they shouldn\u2019t be\u2013but as it stands just on this alone in order to even be a challenge to Ayra\u2019s place amongst Fire Emblem characters you\u2019d basically have to be written\u2026as Ayra. And I\u2019m a big proponent of characters being their own person so while archetypes repeat and newer characters often do draw inspiration from older characters, very few of them are actually one-to-one, and for the best at that. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(35,"p"),e._uU(36," But that\u2019s not where the similarities end. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(37,"p"),e._uU(38," For both Ayra and Kiryu, family plays a big role in their character motivations. Ayra\u2019s loyal to the survival of Isaach, and it\u2019s both her ties to family and country that drove her to flee her homeland as her nephew Shannan\u2019s protector and guardian. Despite Kiryu\u2019s multiple attempts to leave the crime life and Tojo clan behind, ultimately his bonds to the people in it drove him to come back to bail it out of some mess every time and on top of that, a huge part of his character drive after the events of 1 is to raise Haruka. Shannan, in this comparison, occupies both the role of Haruka and Daigo for Ayra, aptly since as of Yakuza 6 Kiryu has also recognized Daigo as his son. The Haruka comparison is a bit more obvious\u2013Haruka/Shannan is a child in the care of Kiryu/Ayra that is a big part of the adult\u2019s character motivations for their actions. Shannan also draws parallel to Daigo in relation to the Ayra-Kiryu comparison, as he\u2019s the successor to the country/Tojo Clan that Ayra/Kiryu places their hopes for the future on. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(39,"p"),e._uU(40," Both Kiryu and Ayra are also immensely loyal to people they care about to a point of ride or die\u2013Kiryu coming back to save the Tojo repeatedly, as stated prior, is mainly due to his bonds to the people in it, rather than a desire to continue being involved in organized crime past Yakuza 2. Hell, in 5, Kiryu was adamant trying to not get involved again until he found out about Majima\u2019s \u201cdeath\u201d and immediately packed his bags back to Tokyo to find out who did it, with some very threatening words for Baba during their fight where he suspected that Baba killed Majima. Ayra has less character connections, being a supporting character, but the development of her relationship to Sigurd from wary enemies-turned-allies-for-Shannan\u2019s-sake to ride-or-die homies where Ayra could\u2019ve left before Belhalla and chose not to, instead fight to the end with Sigurd, also shows immense loyalty to friends on her end. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(41,"p"),e._uU(42," Ayra\u2019s most iconic moment is her introduction, where she threatens Kinbois with his head on a stick if he should double-cross her and Kinbois shows clear fear despite being the one with an army. Without Shannan as leverage, he\u2019s not confident he and his whole army could win against a single Ayra. This introduction of Ayra stuck with me as one of the coolest character introductions in all of Fire Emblem, even after technology advanced to the level of having full animated cutscenes. Ayra felt like a real threat and absolutely capable of following up on it, even if she\u2019ll fight through an army to do so. In Yakuza 6, Kiryu tanks 10 hits to the head with an iron pipe\u2013an absolutely ridiculous feat\u2013and a few extra punches on top of that\u2013because Haruka\u2019s being threatened at gunpoint. Once his homies arrive and disable the immediate threat to Haruka\u2013akin to Sigurd saving Shannan\u2013Kiryu was able to get up despite his injuries and wipe the floor with the Yomei Alliance, despite his injuries. Both events exude a similar sort of energy in protective guardian-ness under duress, but also well-establishes character threat level. "),e.qZA(),e.TgZ(43,"p"),e._uU(44," When 3 Houses first came out, before I read all the supports, I wondered if I\u2019d like anyone more than Ayra. While I\u2019ve found characters I\u2019ve become very attached to, and I greatly enjoy the character writing and its overall support quality is my favorite amongst all Fire Emblems, nevertheless there was none who could approach Ayra. Now I understand that only Ayra herself, as far as being limited to the Fire Emblem format goes, could surpass Ayra. Kiryu himself has 7 games worth of being the protagonist as my absolute top while being the absolute poster boy of My Type. Ayra does a good chunk of it with a handful of lines in a SNES game, written almost 10 years before the first Kiryu game even existed. Within the Fire Emblem writing format, the only way to do \u201cbetter\u201d is just be Ayra but more fleshed out, and that\u2019s only possible if it\u2019s Ayra in a FE4 remake. Other characters? Don\u2019t stand a chance. "),e.qZA()())}}),t})()}];var g=o(7957);let p=(()=>{class t{}return t.\u0275fac=function(a){return new(a||t)},t.\u0275mod=e.oAB({type:t}),t.\u0275inj=e.cJS({imports:[d.ez,r.Bz.forChild(c),g.r]}),t})()}}]);